 pressure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiastolic pressure plus one-third of pulse pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct formula for calculating mean arterial pressure (MAP). This reflects that approximately one-third of the cardiac cycle is spent in systole and two-thirds in diastole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMAP=Diastolic\u00a0BP+ 1/3\u200b\u00d7(Systolic\u00a0BP\u2212Diastolic\u00a0BP)\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor example, if blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, the pulse pressure is 40 mmHg (120-80). MAP would therefore be 80 + (40/3) = 93 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mean arterial pressure is calculated as diastolic pressure plus one-third of pulse pressure.","Mean arterial pressure represents the average pressure driving blood flow through the systemic circulation during the cardiac cycle.","Pulse pressure is the difference between systolic and diastolic blood pressure."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T10:11:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T10:11:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9557"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi